ion":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Rafin","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Jewish Hyman, Ephraim, Meyer, Morry, Moysey, Myer, Ofer, Rivkah, Shimon, Shira, Shoshanna.","Jewish (eastern Ashkenazic): status name for a rabbi, from Polish, Ukrainian, and Belorussian <i>rabin</i> ‘rabbi’, ultimately from Hebrew <i>rav</i>.","French (southern): derivative of   Raba   ‘turnip, oilseed rape’."],"variants":[{"name":"Rabinovich","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Russian Boris, Mikhail, Leonid, Vladimir, Yefim, Aleksandr, Igor, Iosif, Lev, Arkadiy, Arkady, Grigoriy.  Jewish Yakov, Naum, Aron, Isaak, Moisey, Isak, Moysey, Basya.","Jewish (eastern Ashkenazic): patronymic from   Rabin  , formed with the East Slavic patronymic ending <i>-ovich</i>."]},{"name":"Rapin","meanings":["French:","derivative of Old French <i>rapine</i> ‘pillage’ (from Latin <i>rapina</i>), used as a nickname for a rapacious person or a thief.","alternatively, a variant of   Rabin   2, a topographic name denoting residence on ravined terrain, ultimately of the same etymology as 1 above."]},{"name":"Raba","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Manfred.","Polish: status name from <i>rab</i> ‘servant; slave’, or an altered form of German   Rabe  . Compare Hungarian and Czech name   Rab  .","Czech: variant of   Rab   or a nickname from the dialect <i>rabit se</i> ‘to get excited’."]},{"name":"Raben","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Jewish Hymen.","German: from an ancient Germanic personal name containing the element <i>hraban</i> ‘raven’.","Jewish (Ashkenazic): variant of   Rabin  ."]},{"name":"Rabine","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Kurt, Reinhardt.","Jewish: variant of   Rabin  .","Americanized form of German   Rehbein  ."]}]},{"name":"Gilbert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Old French name of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>gisil</i> ‘pledge’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’. It was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to Britain. This was the name of the founder of the only native British religious order (abolished at the Dissolution of the Monasteries),  St Gilbert  of Sempringham (  ?1083–1189 ), in whose honour it is still sometimes bestowed, especially among Roman Catholics. It gained a wider currency in the 19th century."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Gilbert de Rafin I was born about 1086, in Warnham, Sussex, England, United Kingdom as the son of Rafin and Mrs Rafin. He married Mrs Gilbert de Rafin I before 1109, in England. They were the parents of at least 2 sons. He died in South Stoke, Sussex, England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"um 1086–":"umbes 1086–Surnud","1080–Female":"1080–Surnud","1084–Female":"1084–Surnud","1086–Male":"1086–Surnud","–Female":"Surnud","1109–Male":"1109–Surnud","1115–Male":"1115–Surnud","1055–1086":"1055–1086","1080":"1080","1115":"1115","um 1086":"umbes 1086","1055":"1055","about 1115":"umbes 1115","1086":"1086","before 1109":"enne 1109","1084":"1084","1109":"1109","before 1080":"enne 1080","Scotton, Lincolnshire, England":"Scotton, Lincolnshire, England","England":"England","South Stoke, Worthing, Sussex, England":"South Stoke, Sussex, Inglismaa, U